Yes, it is possible to split this up into multiple methods. And you should.

Think about the various tasks being accomplished by your app. Think about responsibilities, think about jobs to be performed. And think about data to be kept and managed. Then think about naming &#160;naming that fits well helps to clarify ones thinking.

As [commented][1] by Kuhn, I too see three jobs here: 

 - Gathering input from a user
 - Tracking that input, and sorting the data.
 - Reporting that data.

With that in mind, I wrote this example class.

```java
package work.basil.example.num;

import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.Scanner;

public class DoublesMachine
{
    private final int limit = 3;  // Or 10 as in Question, whatever.
    private double[] doubles;

    public DoublesMachine ( ) { doubles = new double[ limit ]; }

    private void demo ( )
    {
        this.gather();
        this.sort();
        this.report();
    }

    // Use console to gather inputs for a series of double primitive values, collected inta an array.
    private void gather ( )
    {
        try (
                Scanner scanner = new Scanner( System.in ) ;
        )
        {
            System.out.println( &quot;Tracking &quot; + this.limit + &quot; numbers.&quot; );
            int index = 0;
            do
            {
                int ordinal = index + 1;
                System.out.println( &quot;Enter number # &quot; + ordinal + &quot; of &quot; + this.limit + &quot;: &quot; );
                double input = scanner.nextDouble();
                this.doubles[ index ] = input;
                index = index + 1;  // Increment.
            } while ( ( index + 1 ) &lt;= this.limit );
        }
    }

    private void sort ( )
    {
        Arrays.sort( this.doubles );
    }

    private void report ( )
    {
        String output = Arrays.toString( this.doubles );
        System.out.println( &quot;output = &quot; + output );
    }

    public static void main ( String[] args )
    {
        DoublesMachine app = new DoublesMachine();
        app.demo();
    }
}
```

When run:

```none
Tracking 3 numbers.
Enter number # 1 of 3: 
2.2
Enter number # 2 of 3: 
1.1
Enter number # 3 of 3: 
3.3
output = [1.1, 2.2, 3.3]
```

Notice that we moved virtually all the code outside of the `main` method. The `main` method is *not* [object-oriented][2]. It is basically a hack, a necessary evil, to jump-start the execution of your app. Try to minimize code there, and start using objects as soon as possible.

As explained in the comments, always use an integer as the counter of your `for` loop, not a floating-point type like `double`.

Notice how we placed the [`Scanner`][3] instantiation within [try-with-resources][4] syntax. This ensures a [`Closeable`][5] resource such as `Scanner` is automatically closed even if an exception is thrown.

----------

For learning purposes, I suggest you give the above example only a quick glance. Get the general idea, then try writing your own. The learning is in the doing.

By the way, in real work, we would write separate classes. This gives more flexibility, and allows for writing tests. For example, gathering input from a user should be entirely separate from the management of state (the collection of `double` numbers), in a class of its own. But that is beyond the scope of a Java 101 student assignment.





 


